Colin Lamb  <CL7841S@ACAD.DRAKE.EDU> wrote:
}We digress...
   (is this the usenet motto :)

}We have had a political party here in Iowa called the Natural
}Law party.  The leaders and many members are folks from the Maharishi
}(sp?) International University in Fairfield - the Transcendental
}Meditation
}folks.  What they were saying about Natural Law was that if you do
}a scientific study which says something works, and you agree that
}the study shows that it works, you are pretty much obligated to institue
}what the study shows.  Specifically they were talking about a study
}that shows prisoners who practice TM are much less likely to
}go back to their criminal ways after release.  This seems quite logical
}to me.  The effect is that they want Iowa and other places to start
}TM programs in prisons.
}
}I'm personally all for anything which would reduce the criminal impulse,
}especially for those already in jail.  They are right:  When something
}works - and you can demonstrate its benefits - it should be put into
}practice.  To do otherwise is to fly in the face of Nature!

    I'm pretty sure we could show that giving them all thorough
    lobotomies would also reduce their criminal tendencies too.
    (of course, then they'd be fundamentalists and we'd be right
    back in that freedom of religion arena)

John
